1. Hierarchical model with lip cancer data

We consider data about Lip Cancer in Scotland. It refers to 56 counties and to the following variables:

  • id: county id
  • O: observed number of cases of lip cancer
  • E: expected number of cases (adjusted by age and sex)
  • X: exposure variable (percentage of population working in an outdoor environment, i.e.exposed to sun)
library(INLA)

1.1 Poisson-logNormal model

We implement the following Poisson regression model: \[ O_i\sim \mbox{Poisson}(\phi_i E_i) \] where \(\phi_i\) is the relative risk.

The linear predictor is given by \[ \eta_i=\log(\phi_i)=b_0 + v_{i} + b_1 x_i \]

An exchangeable prior is specified on the random effect: \(v_{0i}\sim\mbox{Normal}(0, 1/\tau_{v0})\), with \(\tau_{v0}\) being an hyperparameter. It is internally represented as \(\log\tau_{v0}\) with default prior given by \(\mbox{logGamma}\sim(1, 0.00005)\) (see linkiid).

3. Run INLA 

formula = O ~ 1 + X + f(id,model="iid") #default prior for log tau_v: logGamma(1,5e-05)

lipcancer.poisson = inla(formula,family="poisson",
                           data=LipCancerData, offset=log(E))

summary(lipcancer.poisson)

3. Change the hyperparameter prior

Instead of the default \(\mbox{logGamma}\sim(1, 0.00005)\) prior for \(\log\tau_{v0}\), we want to specify a \(\mbox{logGamma}\sim(1, 0.00001)\):

formula = O ~ 1 + X + 
                f(id,model="iid", 
                  hyper=list(prec=
                               list(prior="loggamma",param=c(1,0.00001))))

lipcancer.poisson2 = inla(formula,family="poisson",
                           data=LipCancerData, offset=log(E),
                            control.compute=list(config = TRUE, #used later 
                                                 dic=TRUE)) 
summary(lipcancer.poisson2)

3. The covariate effect

To estimate the effect of the covariate we compute the posterior mean on the natural scale (\(\exp(b_1)\)):

inla.emarginal(exp,lipcancer.poisson2$marginals.fixed$X)
## [1] 1.070845

We obtain that an increase of 1 unit in the covariate is associated with an increase of around 7% in the risk of lip cancer.

3. Between-area standard deviation \(\sigma_{v0}\)

Remember that with INLA we get the precision \(\tau_v\). We need to transform the posterior marginal:

names(lipcancer.poisson2$marginals.hyperpar)

sigmav0 = inla.tmarginal(function(x) sqrt(1/x), lipcancer.poisson2$marginals.hyperpar[[1]])

The following plot aims to show that, with the hierarchical model, estimated RRs are shrinked towards the mean (less variability than SMRs). We compare the \(SMR_i=y_i/E_i\) with the estimated RRs.

SMR_estRR=cbind(LipCancerData$O/LipCancerData$E, unlist(post.mean.exp.v0))

op = par(mar = c(5,4,4,4) + 0.1)
plot(SMR_estRR[,1],type="n",ylab="SMR",xaxt="n",xlab="")
for(i in 1:56)  segments(1,SMR_estRR[i,1],56,SMR_estRR[i,2])
axis(side = 4)
mtext("estimated RR", side = 4, line = 3, cex = par("cex.lab"))

3. Compute the map of excess risk

We are interested in mapping the excess risk defined as \(p(\exp(v_{0i})>1\mid y)\) or equivalently as \(p(v_{0i}>0\mid y)\). We will use inla.pmarginal(...) function inside lapply:

threshold = 0
post.prob.excess = lapply(lipcancer.poisson2$marginals.random[["id"]],
                          function(x) 1-inla.pmarginal(threshold,x))
range(unlist(post.prob.excess))
## [1] 0.0001082202 0.9999476176
# Save the posterior excess probability in a dataframe
data.prob.excess = data.frame(ID=names(geobugs.map), post.prob=unlist(post.prob.excess))
row.names(data.prob.excess) = names(geobugs.map)
wards = SpatialPolygonsDataFrame(geobugs.map,data.prob.excess)

# Mapping!
spplot(obj=wards, zcol="post.prob",main="")

3. Compute the quantile ratios through simulation

We use the inla.posterior.sample to generate samples from an approximated (joint) posterior of a fitted model. To be run it requires the option control.compute = list(config=TRUE) to be included in the inla(...) function run.

In this case we simulate 50 samples from the joint posterior:

n.sim = 50
joint.post = inla.posterior.sample(n.sim,lipcancer.poisson2)

For each sample (50 in total) we compute the 5th and 95th quantiles (across areas) of log relative risks (\(v_0\)):

n.areas = nrow(LipCancerData)

# Just select the from ...$latent the values of the random effect v_0 and save them in a matrix
joint.v = matrix(NA,n.areas,n.sim)
for(i in 1:n.sim){
        joint.v[,i] = joint.post[[i]]$latent[(n.areas+1):(n.areas*2)]
}

Compute column by column (for each simulation) the 5% and 95% quantile and then compute their ratio and exponentiate:

v5perc = apply(joint.v,2, quantile, 0.05)
v95perc = apply(joint.v,2, quantile, 0.95)
QR90 = mean(exp(v95perc-v5perc)) 
QR90
## [1] 6.319925

3. Compute linear combinations \(\beta_{0i}=b_0+v_{0i}\)

Assume we are interested in obtaining the marginal posterior distribution for \(\beta_{0i}=b_0 + v_{0i}\). To obtain it we have to define the two effects through the inla.make.lincombs command (see Martins et al., 2013). Then in the inla(...) function the linear combination will be included through the lincomb option.

We have to:

  • for the intercept: define a vector of ones with the length given by the number of areas
  • for the random effects: define a matrix with ones on the diagonal with id=diag(n.areas)
lcs = inla.make.lincombs("(Intercept)" = rep(1,n.areas),
                         id = diag(n.areas))

# Check how the lincombs look like 
head(names(lcs))
## [1] "lc01" "lc02" "lc03" "lc04" "lc05" "lc06"
lcs$lc01 
## [[1]]

## 
## 
## [[2]]
## [[2]]$id
## [[2]]$id$idx
## [1] 1
## 
## [[2]]$id$weight
## [1] 1
# Run inla including the lincombs
lipcancer.poisson3 = inla(formula,family="poisson",
                            data=LipCancerData, offset=log(E),
                            control.compute=list(config = TRUE),
                            lincomb=lcs)

3. Random slope model

We want know to change the model to include also a random slope: \[ O_i\sim \mbox{Poisson}(\lambda_i=\rho_i E_i) \] \[ \log(\rho_i)=b_0 + v_{0i} + (b_1+v_{1i}) x_i \] Exchangeable priors are specified on the random effects: \(v_{0i}\sim N(0, 1/\tau_{v0})\) and \(v_{1i}\sim N(0, 1/\tau_{v1})\), with \(\tau_{v0}\) and \(\tau_{v1}\) as hyperparameters. We assume a logGamma(1,0.00001) prior for the log precision.

# Create a new index variable for the new random effect v1
LipCancerData$id2 = LipCancerData$id

formula = O ~ 1 + X +  
        f(id, model="iid",hyper=list(prec=
                               list(prior="loggamma",param=c(1,0.00001)))) +
        f(id2, X, model="iid",hyper=list(prec=
                               list(prior="loggamma",param=c(1,0.00001)))) #covariate X in second position (as weight)

# Define lincombs for beta0i = b0+ v0i
lcs1 = inla.make.lincombs("(Intercept)" = rep(1,n.areas), id = diag(n.areas))
# Define lincombs for beta1i = b1 + v1i
lcs2 = inla.make.lincombs(id = diag(n.areas), X = rep(1,n.areas)) #X is the name for b1

# Check the names
names(lcs1)[1]
## [1] "lc01"
names(lcs2)[1]
## [1] "lc01"
# Note that INLA assigns the same names to each of the linear combinations,
#so we need to change these to avoid errors when running INLA
names(lcs2) = paste(names(lcs1),"X",sep="") 

# Combine all toghether the lincombs
all.lcs = c(lcs1,lcs2)

# Run inla
lipcancer.poisson4 = inla(formula,family="poisson",
                            data=LipCancerData, offset=log(E),
                            control.compute=list(config = TRUE,
                                                 dic=TRUE),
                            lincomb=all.lcs)
summary(lipcancer.poisson4)

With the following code it is possible to map both \(\beta_{0i}=b_0+v_{0i}\) and \(\beta_{1i}=b_1+v_{1i}\) for all the areas on the natural scale:

# Compute exponentiated posterior means
post.mean.exp.beta0 = lapply(lipcancer.poisson4$marginals.lincomb.derived[1:n.areas],
                             function(x) inla.emarginal(exp,x))
post.mean.exp.beta1 = lapply(lipcancer.poisson4$marginals.lincomb.derived[(n.areas+1):(n.areas*2)],
                             function(x) inla.emarginal(exp,x))

# Combine everything in a dataframe
data.lcs.beta0_beta1 = data.frame(ID=names(geobugs.map), post.mean.exp.beta0=unlist(post.mean.exp.beta0),
                                  post.mean.exp.beta1=unlist(post.mean.exp.beta1))
row.names(data.lcs.beta0_beta1) = names(geobugs.map)


wards = SpatialPolygonsDataFrame(geobugs.map,data.lcs.beta0_beta1)
names(wards)
## [1] "ID"                  "post.mean.exp.beta0" "post.mean.exp.beta1"
spplot(obj=wards, zcol=c("post.mean.exp.beta0","post.mean.exp.beta1"),main="")

3. Model comparison using DIC

Lets compare the two models (one with random intercepts and the other with random slopes). To get DIC the option control.compute=list(dic=TRUE) has to be specified.

names(lipcancer.poisson4$dic)
##  [1] "dic"               "p.eff"             "mean.deviance"     "deviance.mean"    
##  [5] "dic.sat"           "mean.deviance.sat" "deviance.mean.sat" "family.dic"       
##  [9] "family.dic.sat"    "family.p.eff"      "family"            "local.dic"        
## [13] "local.dic.sat"     "local.p.eff"
lipcancer.poisson4$dic$dic #model with random slopes
## [1] 310.5109
lipcancer.poisson2$dic$dic #model with random intercepts
## [1] 310.7653

It is possible to obtain other cross-validated predictive measures such as

  • conditional predictive ordinate (cpo): \(p(y_i\mid y_{-i})\)
  • probability integral transformation (pit): \(p(y_i^\mbox{new} \leq y_i\mid y_{-i})\)

with the option control.compute=list(cpo=TRUE).
